# React Rules

## Component Design

- Use **functional components** exclusively; avoid class components.
- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility.
- Co-locate component files with their styles and tests.
- Use named exports for components; reserve default exports for page-level components.

## Hooks

- Call hooks only at the top level — never inside loops, conditions, or nested functions.
- Use `useState` for local UI state; lift state up only when siblings need it.
- Use `useEffect` for side effects; always specify a dependency array.
- Clean up subscriptions, timers, and event listeners in the `useEffect` return function.
- Extract reusable stateful logic into custom hooks (`use` prefix required).
- Prefer `useReducer` over multiple related `useState` calls for complex state.
- Use `useMemo` to memoize expensive computations; use `useCallback` to stabilize function references passed as props.

## Props & Types

- Define prop types with **TypeScript interfaces**; avoid `any`.
- Mark optional props explicitly with `?`.
- Destructure props at the function signature level.
- Use `React.FC<Props>` sparingly — prefer plain function signatures with typed parameters.
- Pass only the props a component needs; avoid prop drilling more than two levels deep (use Context or a state manager instead).

## Performance

- Wrap pure child components with `React.memo` to prevent unnecessary re-renders.
- Use `React.lazy` + `Suspense` for code-splitting route-level and heavy components.
- Avoid creating objects or functions inline inside JSX when they are used as props for memoized children.
- Use the **React DevTools Profiler** to identify and fix performance bottlenecks before optimising speculatively.

## State Management

- Use React Context for low-frequency global state (theme, locale, auth user).
- Use Zustand, Redux Toolkit, or Jotai for high-frequency or complex shared state.
- Keep derived data out of state — compute it from existing state during render or with `useMemo`.

## Styling

- Prefer CSS Modules or a CSS-in-JS library (e.g., styled-components, Emotion) for component-scoped styles.
- Avoid inline `style` objects for anything beyond truly dynamic values.

## Event Handling

- Name event handler props `onX` (e.g., `onClick`, `onChange`).
- Name handler implementations `handleX` inside the component.

## Accessibility

- Use semantic HTML elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, etc.) instead of styled `<div>` wrappers.
- Always provide meaningful `alt` text for `<img>` elements.
- Ensure interactive elements are keyboard-navigable.
- Use `aria-*` attributes only when native semantics are insufficient.

## File & Folder Structure

```
src/
  components/        # Shared/reusable components
  features/          # Feature-scoped components, hooks, slices
  hooks/             # Global custom hooks
  pages/ (or routes/)
  utils/
  types/
```

## Testing

- Test behaviour, not implementation details.
- Use **React Testing Library** with `userEvent` for interaction tests.
- Mock external dependencies (API calls, context) at the module level.
- Write at least one test per component covering its primary use case.
